 216 |     - Exploitation means refining a promising family after it shows improvement.
 217 |       Use it for small, controlled changes that preserve the useful behavior
 218 |       while addressing a clear limitation such as scaling, baseline behavior,
 219 |       numerical conditioning, or unnecessary complexity.
 220 |     - If recent child scores regress or duplicate the current best, switch from
 221 |       incremental tweaks to evidence gathering. Inspect run history, hard cases,
 222 |       and, when useful, external sources before proposing the next expression.
 223 |     - If a child improves substantially, exploit that direction with minimal
 224 |       changes rather than immediately replacing the whole structure.
 225 | 
 226 |     Before changing the expression, identify the most likely limitation:
 227 |     - poor fit quality on many datasets
 228 |     - non-finite predictions or invalid arithmetic on one or more datasets
 229 |     - excessive sensitivity to x0 or x1 scaling
 230 |     - over-parameterization that makes constant fitting unreliable
 231 |     - under-parameterization that cannot capture shared structure
 232 |     - a redundant term that adds complexity without improving robustness
 233 | 
 234 |     Prefer the smallest structural change that targets the limitation you
 235 |     identify. Do not add complexity merely because more constants are allowed.
 236 |     Because complexity has a small direct score penalty, every extra operation
 237 |     or fitted constant should have a clear expected payoff in validation fit or
 238 |     robustness.
 239 | 
 240 |     Good candidates are:
 241 |     - smooth and globally defined over the observed x0 and x1 ranges
 242 |     - numerically stable during least-squares fitting
 243 |     - compact enough for reliable optimization from one initial point
 244 |     - able to use x1 when it is informative without depending on it too strongly
 245 |     - robust on small, noisy, or unusually scaled datasets
 246 | 
 247 |     Be especially cautious with operations that can create singularities,
 248 |     non-real values, overflow, or invalid powers during fitting. If you use
 249 |     division, exponentials, logarithms, square roots, or variable exponents,
 250 |     explain why the resulting expression remains well behaved.
 251 | 
 252 |     Keep the number of fitted constants moderate. Too many constants risk
 253 |     unstable fits on small datasets; too few can underfit shared structure.
 254 | 
 255 |     ## Constraints
 256 |     - Exactly one call to `evaluate_expression(...)` per
 257 |       `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` invocation.
 258 |     - Directly `return evaluate_expression(...)`; do not assign the result to a
 259 |       variable, edit it, wrap it, or post-process it.
 260 |     - The `equation_template` returned by the scorer must be identical for every
 261 |       dataset; only fitted constant values may differ across datasets.
 262 |     - Keep `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` straight-line: no loops, conditionals,
 263 |       try/except blocks, nested functions/classes, comprehensions, helper
 264 |       function calls, or imports inside the function.
 265 |     - Do not use `Piecewise`, `Max`, `Min`, `sign`, `floor`, `ceiling`,
